1
00:03:20,896 --> 00:03:26,573
My name is Karl Glocken, and
this is a ship of fools.

2
00:03:27,256 --> 00:03:30,407
l'm a fool. And you'll meet
more fools as we go along.

3
00:03:30,496 --> 00:03:32,407
This tub is packed with them.

4
00:03:33,336 --> 00:03:36,408
Emancipated ladies. Ball players.

5
00:03:36,816 --> 00:03:38,966
Lovers. Dog lovers.

6
00:03:39,656 --> 00:03:43,251
Ladies of joy. Tolerant Jews.

7
00:03:43,896 --> 00:03:46,649
Dwarfs. All kinds.

8
00:03:46,776 --> 00:03:50,166
And who knows, if you
look closely enough..

9
00:03:50,256 --> 00:03:53,248
..you may even find
yourself on board.

10
00:03:56,976 --> 00:03:58,489
Good morning, doctor.

11
00:03:59,256 --> 00:04:00,575
Good morning.

12
00:04:27,176 --> 00:04:28,768
l'm glad to get out of Veracruz.

13
00:04:28,856 --> 00:04:31,416
The whole damn country
is ready to explode.

14
00:04:32,256 --> 00:04:35,646
Well, did you get a look at them?
Anything interesting?

15
00:04:36,256 --> 00:04:37,814
Anything interesting at all?

16
00:04:38,656 --> 00:04:40,965
There's a dwarf, that high.

17
00:04:42,336 --> 00:04:44,566
A couple of young American painters.

18
00:04:44,656 --> 00:04:48,808
And a Jewish salesman with an
infectious sense of humor.

19
00:04:48,896 --> 00:04:50,648
Women, Willie. Women.

20
00:04:51,736 --> 00:04:55,251
Well, a rather attractive
middle-aged American woman.

21
00:04:55,896 --> 00:04:58,729
But l'm afraid she's too far
from the cradle for you.

22
00:04:58,816 --> 00:05:01,967
Those are the kind that can sometime
appreciate what they are getting.

23
00:05:02,416 --> 00:05:06,967
There's a Spanish dancing troupe,
interesting, but maybe professional.

24
00:05:07,056 --> 00:05:09,365
They've had those Spanish dance
troupes on board before.

25
00:05:09,456 --> 00:05:12,334
And the usual assortment
of our countrywomen.

26
00:05:12,416 --> 00:05:15,169
Professors' wives? Saleswomen
putting on airs?

27
00:05:15,256 --> 00:05:17,326
- l'm afraid so. - Governesses?

28
00:05:18,736 --> 00:05:20,567
- Maybe you shouldn't.
- That's all right.

29
00:05:21,656 --> 00:05:23,965
You're really getting off
at Bremerhaven, huh?

30
00:05:24,176 --> 00:05:27,327
lt wasn't a very long career.
Three voyages.

31
00:05:27,736 --> 00:05:28,885
Long enough.

32
00:05:29,376 --> 00:05:31,970
l don't know what the hell l'm
going to do without you.

33
00:05:32,176 --> 00:05:33,575
You'll manage.

34
00:05:35,416 --> 00:05:38,647
You want to know the sentimental,
disgusting truth?

35
00:05:41,336 --> 00:05:44,567
l've become fonder of you than
of most people in my life.

36
00:05:46,816 --> 00:05:48,807
We just got used to each
other, that's all.

37
00:05:50,816 --> 00:05:54,650
Who am l to play chess with?
Who am l to talk to?

38
00:05:54,776 --> 00:05:57,574
You've seen the kind of characters
we get on this ship.

39
00:05:58,416 --> 00:06:01,965
l get a cold shudder every time l
have to go to the captain's table.

40
00:06:02,896 --> 00:06:05,251
l must be in my dotage.

41
00:06:06,416 --> 00:06:07,565
After my..

42
00:06:11,816 --> 00:06:13,727
l was looking for something.

43
00:06:13,816 --> 00:06:16,808
l thought l could learn something
new by being a ship's doctor.

44
00:06:18,256 --> 00:06:21,726
But l've seen all this before. l've
seen all these people before.

45
00:06:22,736 --> 00:06:24,408
Never on a ship, that's all.

46
00:06:25,176 --> 00:06:26,575
Come in.

47
00:06:26,816 --> 00:06:29,330
- Lunch is served, captain.
- Thank you.

48
00:06:32,256 --> 00:06:33,575
Please?

49
00:06:38,176 --> 00:06:41,646
- What should l tell them this
time? - Tell them anything you like.

50
00:06:42,816 --> 00:06:44,966
Tell them l had to fix the toilets.

51
00:07:00,496 --> 00:07:03,568
1933 will be a good year.
l am optimistic.

52
00:07:03,656 --> 00:07:06,489
At any rate, it is starting
out most auspiciously.

53
00:07:06,816 --> 00:07:10,491
Ah it is good to be on a German
boat with German people, going home.

54
00:07:10,576 --> 00:07:14,489
Say what you will, there is a feeling
when German people get together.

55
00:07:14,576 --> 00:07:17,409
l cannot explain it. 'Gemutliche
Kameraderie..'

56
00:07:17,496 --> 00:07:19,407
..which exists among
no other people.

57
00:07:19,496 --> 00:07:21,327
At least l have found
it nowhere else.

58
00:07:21,416 --> 00:07:22,815
You know what they say in Mexico?

59
00:07:22,896 --> 00:07:25,888
Mexicans loathe the Americans,
hate the Spaniards..

60
00:07:25,976 --> 00:07:29,571
..distrust the English, admire
the French and love the Germans.

61
00:07:29,656 --> 00:07:32,170
That is all very nice. l am glad
that they say those things.

62
00:07:32,256 --> 00:07:36,169
But as far as l am concerned,
after a few weeks in Mexico..

63
00:07:36,256 --> 00:07:37,894
..you can keep the Mexicans too.

64
00:07:38,896 --> 00:07:41,888
How long has it been since you
have been home, Herr Freytag?

65
00:07:42,896 --> 00:07:45,649
- Four months. - You must be
glad to be going home too.

66
00:07:45,776 --> 00:07:47,573
Yes, my wife is there.

67
00:07:48,176 --> 00:07:50,736
Why is it that every charming
man l meet is married?

68
00:07:50,816 --> 00:07:53,569
Fraulein Spockenkieker, you
have wounded to me the quick.

69
00:07:53,656 --> 00:07:55,726
Excepting you, Herr Rieber.
l'm sorry.

70
00:07:58,656 --> 00:08:01,170
That little dog is so sweet.

71
00:08:01,256 --> 00:08:04,168
He has shared so much of the
professor's life and mine..

72
00:08:04,256 --> 00:08:07,328
..l feel sometimes
he is like our son.

73
00:08:07,576 --> 00:08:10,329
Do you think it's correct to
bring a dog to the table?

74
00:08:13,176 --> 00:08:15,485
Bebe goes with us everywhere.

75
00:08:15,896 --> 00:08:19,571
We have taken him to some
of the best restaurants.

76
00:08:21,336 --> 00:08:23,327
Nobody seems to mind.

77
00:08:26,816 --> 00:08:28,966
You know, it's gonna be
a wonderful trip, David.

78
00:08:31,176 --> 00:08:33,736
l still feel funny about
you picking up the tab.

79
00:08:33,816 --> 00:08:37,411
Look, we weren't gonna
talk about that.

80
00:08:41,256 --> 00:08:44,328
Did l ever tell you these have been
the best three months of my life?

81
00:08:45,816 --> 00:08:49,331
Did l ever tell you that l care for
you so much it's very upsetting?

82
00:08:54,336 --> 00:08:56,327
What? What's the matter?

83
00:08:57,336 --> 00:09:01,568
Twenty-six days in separate beds.

84
00:09:02,736 --> 00:09:04,727
lt's probably a very good thing.

85
00:09:05,896 --> 00:09:07,648
We'll get to know each other.

86
00:09:08,776 --> 00:09:12,564
We'll find out whether we have
anything going for us besides sex.

87
00:09:14,416 --> 00:09:16,327
l give you one more time
to hang yourself.

88
00:09:16,416 --> 00:09:17,815
l know you got more
money from the Swede.

89
00:09:17,896 --> 00:09:19,887
- l gave you what l got. - The
barman told me different.

90
00:09:19,976 --> 00:09:21,170
He is a liar.

91
00:09:21,256 --> 00:09:23,895
lf you're holding out on me, l
swear l'll rip your lying tongue out.

92
00:09:23,976 --> 00:09:25,773
Rip my guts out. l don't
have any more money.

93
00:09:35,056 --> 00:09:36,728
l asked for a table alone.

94
00:09:36,816 --> 00:09:39,649
l'm sorry, madame, there is
no room for a table alone.

95
00:09:45,416 --> 00:09:47,327
Please don't bother getting up.

96
00:09:52,656 --> 00:09:53,884
You're an American?

97
00:09:54,336 --> 00:09:57,965
- And my name's Bill Tenny.
- Mary Treadwell.

98
00:09:58,896 --> 00:10:00,329
Yes, madam?

99
00:10:01,816 --> 00:10:06,651
l'll have the pate and the
Rheinischer Sauerbraten.

100
00:10:08,256 --> 00:10:10,167
- You, sir? - You got a steak?

101
00:10:10,256 --> 00:10:11,325
- Yes, sir. - Thick?

102
00:10:11,416 --> 00:10:12,735
We will do our best.

103
00:10:16,976 --> 00:10:18,967
l'd better stick to
the simple stuff.

104
00:10:19,176 --> 00:10:20,575
You know l was in Veracruz trying..

105
00:10:20,656 --> 00:10:21,975
..to teach them greasers
how to play the ball.

106
00:10:22,056 --> 00:10:23,887
Man, they tried to poison me.

107
00:10:23,976 --> 00:10:26,331
You know, l had the
runs for three weeks.

108
00:10:27,656 --> 00:10:29,248
How interesting.

109
00:10:30,416 --> 00:10:32,054
l'd like to hear more about it.

110
00:10:34,816 --> 00:10:38,570
Herr Rieber, l hear that you
publish a national magazine..

111
00:10:38,656 --> 00:10:40,886
..with certain intellectual
features.

112
00:10:40,976 --> 00:10:45,174
A garment trade magazine,
but modern. Modern.

113
00:10:45,256 --> 00:10:48,168
Good afternoon. l'm Willie
Schumann, the ship's doctor.

114
00:10:48,256 --> 00:10:49,814
The captain sends his regrets.

115
00:10:49,896 --> 00:10:52,649
He's unable to come to lunch,
because of ship's business.

116
00:10:52,736 --> 00:10:54,772
Doctor, l am Siegfried Rieber.

117
00:10:54,856 --> 00:10:56,653
This is Professor Hutten,
Frau Hutten.

118
00:10:56,736 --> 00:10:59,330
- Please. - No, no allow me.
And their dog, Bebe.

119
00:10:59,656 --> 00:11:01,965
This charming young lady is
Fraulein Spockenkieker.

120
00:11:02,056 --> 00:11:05,890
Herr Freytag, Frau Schmitt, Herr
Graf and his nephew Johann.

121
00:11:05,976 --> 00:11:08,171
Please don't let me interrupt
your conversations.

122
00:11:08,256 --> 00:11:10,486
We were just discussing
Herr Rieber's magazine.

123
00:11:10,576 --> 00:11:12,965
Yes l have invited talented writers
from all over the nation..

124
00:11:13,056 --> 00:11:14,887
..to contribute on one topic:

125
00:11:14,976 --> 00:11:17,649
How we can expunge foreign
influences..

126
00:11:17,736 --> 00:11:20,330
..and restore Germany to
its national greatness.

127
00:11:20,416 --> 00:11:22,247
What foreign influences?

128
00:11:32,656 --> 00:11:35,489
lf you need any attendance,
l'll be at your disposal.

129
00:11:35,576 --> 00:11:36,645
Thank you.

130
00:11:36,736 --> 00:11:41,332
On my part, doctor, you need
have no concern for me.

131
00:11:41,656 --> 00:11:45,171
l do not believe in
'materia medica.'

132
00:11:45,256 --> 00:11:46,575
Really?

133
00:11:47,176 --> 00:11:49,565
Have you found something
better to replace it?

134
00:11:50,656 --> 00:11:53,648
- Faith. - Faith. l see. Very well.

135
00:11:53,776 --> 00:11:58,725
A toast. A toast to the German
woman, the most beautiful in the world.

136
00:12:03,736 --> 00:12:05,966
- Delicious. - Herr Rieber.

137
00:12:15,816 --> 00:12:17,966
- Good afternoon. - Good afternoon.

138
00:12:18,176 --> 00:12:20,736
- Karl Glocken. - Julius Lowenthal.

139
00:12:22,896 --> 00:12:24,409
The herring is very good.

140
00:12:26,176 --> 00:12:28,974
l'll have that and a couple
of hard-boiled eggs.

141
00:12:33,336 --> 00:12:34,655
l beg your pardon.

142
00:12:35,736 --> 00:12:37,567
You aren't Jewish, are you?

143
00:12:38,816 --> 00:12:41,728
No. l have my own minority group.

144
00:12:42,496 --> 00:12:46,330
They usually give a Jew a table
of his own on a boat like this.

145
00:12:46,416 --> 00:12:48,372
Why do you think they
put us together?

146
00:12:48,656 --> 00:12:50,647
lt's their way of being friendly.

147
00:12:50,736 --> 00:12:52,886
Perhaps they thought
we might hit it off.

148
00:13:00,976 --> 00:13:03,888
You are sure you are not Jewish?

149
00:13:05,816 --> 00:13:07,329
Reasonably sure.

150
00:13:07,816 --> 00:13:10,410
You resemble a brother-in-law
of mine in Stuttgart.

151
00:13:11,496 --> 00:13:12,815
That's the way it is.

152
00:13:12,896 --> 00:13:15,569
People are always mistaking
me for someone else.

153
00:13:17,336 --> 00:13:19,645
- Spot of wine? - Just a touch.

154
00:13:51,256 --> 00:13:53,816
My God. Where are we
going to put them?

155
00:13:54,256 --> 00:13:55,575
We'll have to manage.

156
00:14:24,776 --> 00:14:27,336
Professor, what is it?

157
00:14:27,416 --> 00:14:30,806
What's happening? Who
are all those people?

158
00:14:30,896 --> 00:14:33,171
There's nothing to be concerned
about Frau Schmitt.

159
00:14:33,256 --> 00:14:36,805
- l have spoken to one of the
officials. - But what is it?

160
00:14:36,896 --> 00:14:40,332
lt has to do with the price
of sugar on the world market.

161
00:14:40,416 --> 00:14:42,247
- Sugar? - Yeah. You see..

162
00:14:42,336 --> 00:14:44,975
..the sugar planters have been
unable to get their price..

163
00:14:45,056 --> 00:14:46,375
..so they burned their crops..

164
00:14:46,456 --> 00:14:49,050
..in the fields rather than
let the prices go down.

165
00:14:49,496 --> 00:14:52,966
Something had to be done about
the Spanish laborers..

166
00:14:53,256 --> 00:14:56,726
..so the Cuban government hit upon
a humanitarian plan of action.

167
00:14:56,816 --> 00:14:58,329
They're sending them home.

168
00:16:21,496 --> 00:16:23,726
- How do you feel? - 'Bien.'

169
00:16:23,816 --> 00:16:25,249
Good.

170
00:16:26,816 --> 00:16:28,727
l come to see you later, yes?

171
00:16:29,896 --> 00:16:31,648
Please put her there in the corner.

172
00:16:45,896 --> 00:16:48,410
- Where can they wash?
-There are two spigots.

173
00:16:48,656 --> 00:16:51,375
- What?! - lt is not my fault.

174
00:16:51,456 --> 00:16:53,333
Stop talking to me in this way.

175
00:16:53,816 --> 00:16:55,408
You just don't put 600 people..

176
00:16:55,496 --> 00:16:57,646
..on a deck like this with
only two outlets to wash!

177
00:16:57,736 --> 00:16:58,771
You don't know them.

178
00:16:58,856 --> 00:17:00,972
They wouldn't wash if they could.
You don't know what pigs they are.

179
00:17:01,056 --> 00:17:03,172
The deck has to be cleaned.
Bring the hoses out.

180
00:17:03,256 --> 00:17:04,814
- The hoses? - Bring the
hoses out, l said!

181
00:17:04,896 --> 00:17:06,329
l cannot turn hoses on them.

182
00:17:06,416 --> 00:17:07,815
lt's better to turn
the hoses on them..

183
00:17:07,896 --> 00:17:09,375
..than for them to
live this way, no?

184
00:17:11,816 --> 00:17:14,649
- Break out the hoses.
- Turn on those hoses.

185
00:18:28,816 --> 00:18:31,250
l take it you are not
exactly pleased..

186
00:18:31,336 --> 00:18:33,770
..that we are cabin
mates on this voyage.

187
00:18:33,856 --> 00:18:36,768
l have already requested a change
in the accommodations.

188
00:18:37,176 --> 00:18:38,370
You may take it from me..

189
00:18:38,456 --> 00:18:41,414
..that l'm not exactly overwhelmed
with the prospect either.

190
00:18:41,576 --> 00:18:43,965
However, pending changes..

191
00:18:44,056 --> 00:18:47,173
..since we are captives of each
other's company for 26 days..

192
00:18:47,256 --> 00:18:50,328
..l think it is best if we
reach an understanding.

193
00:18:51,816 --> 00:18:54,171
Our cosmetics, for instance..

194
00:18:54,256 --> 00:18:58,408
..l will keep mine on
this side of the sink.

195
00:18:58,656 --> 00:19:02,569
And you keep yours on that
side. That's right?

196
00:19:04,176 --> 00:19:07,646
Which bunk do you prefer?
The lower or the upper?

197
00:19:09,896 --> 00:19:11,648
l was assured the lower.

198
00:19:12,336 --> 00:19:13,655
lt is yours.

199
00:19:14,776 --> 00:19:16,255
What are your habits?

200
00:19:16,496 --> 00:19:19,249
l, myself, rise very
early in the morning.

201
00:19:19,816 --> 00:19:24,651
l take it that if this evening is
an example, you are a late bird.

202
00:19:25,256 --> 00:19:28,487
lf you sleep late, l will see
that l do not disturb you.

203
00:19:30,816 --> 00:19:35,492
And l hope you, in turn, will try
your best not to disturb me.

204
00:19:41,256 --> 00:19:42,575
One other thing.

205
00:19:46,736 --> 00:19:48,249
One other thing.

206
00:19:49,416 --> 00:19:53,648
My wife has informed me in the most
sarcastic terms possible..

207
00:19:53,976 --> 00:19:55,329
..l snore.

208
00:19:58,416 --> 00:19:59,565
Good night.

209
00:20:00,256 --> 00:20:01,974
- You a painter, huh? - Yeah.

210
00:20:02,056 --> 00:20:05,173
- What was you doing in Mexico?
- l was a timekeeper in a mine.

211
00:20:05,256 --> 00:20:06,735
l thought you said
you was a painter.

212
00:20:06,816 --> 00:20:08,966
l am a painter, but l was
a timekeeper in a mine.

213
00:20:09,056 --> 00:20:12,253
- Why? - To support
myself as a painter.

214
00:20:12,336 --> 00:20:14,566
- What's the matter? Don't you
make any money painting? - No.

215
00:20:14,736 --> 00:20:17,773
Oh now, wait a minute.
Come on. Wait a minute.

216
00:20:17,856 --> 00:20:21,565
You mean to tell me you work at
something you can't make a living off..

217
00:20:21,656 --> 00:20:23,567
..so you gotta take a job
to make enough money..

218
00:20:23,656 --> 00:20:25,806
..to go on working at
work you can't live on?

219
00:20:25,896 --> 00:20:27,727
But that is the heroic life.

220
00:20:27,816 --> 00:20:32,253
That is the way men who trust
themselves can afford to live.

221
00:20:32,816 --> 00:20:35,171
- A strange neck of the woods.
- What do you mean?

222
00:20:35,256 --> 00:20:36,894
Strange neck of the woods.

223
00:20:37,336 --> 00:20:39,645
Look, l run into all kinds
of people, you know, but..

224
00:20:40,336 --> 00:20:42,406
Did l tell you what happened
to a guy in Veracruz..

225
00:20:42,496 --> 00:20:43,895
..when l was coming
through immigration?

226
00:20:43,976 --> 00:20:46,251
Well l'm standing in line see.
So l see this clerk..

227
00:20:46,336 --> 00:20:48,247
..and l holler, Hey, Pancho,
get over here.

228
00:20:48,336 --> 00:20:49,564
Just being friendly-like..

229
00:20:49,736 --> 00:20:51,966
..like back home you call
a taxi driver Mac

230
00:20:52,056 --> 00:20:53,648
..or a Pullman porter George.

231
00:20:53,776 --> 00:20:55,653
Well this little Negro..
You know these coast..

232
00:20:55,736 --> 00:20:57,567
..Mexicans got mostly Negro
blood in them, l'm told.

233
00:20:57,656 --> 00:20:59,647
Well, he just looks
up and stares at me.

234
00:20:59,776 --> 00:21:03,815
The next thing l know, everybody's
going ahead of me in this line.

235
00:21:04,336 --> 00:21:07,646
Then l realize that this
little Negro resented it.

236
00:21:09,736 --> 00:21:12,569
- l think l'll turn in. - Me too.

237
00:21:25,056 --> 00:21:26,330
Come in.

238
00:21:27,376 --> 00:21:29,253
- Good evening. - Good evening.

239
00:21:31,736 --> 00:21:33,647
l'm the doctor. You
wanted to see me?

240
00:21:33,736 --> 00:21:37,251
Yes. l need something
to help me sleep.

241
00:21:37,336 --> 00:21:38,894
- Are you ill? - No, no.

242
00:21:38,976 --> 00:21:40,887
l just want something
to help me sleep.

243
00:21:41,816 --> 00:21:44,774
- Do you often have trouble
sleeping? - Yes. Always.

244
00:21:46,176 --> 00:21:49,964
- Does your doctor help you to
sleep? - Yes. Occasionally.

245
00:21:50,256 --> 00:21:51,655
Take off your robe.

246
00:21:51,896 --> 00:21:55,969
- You're sure you're the ship's
doctor? - Oh l am the ship's doctor.

247
00:22:04,056 --> 00:22:05,330
Lean forward, please.

248
00:22:09,656 --> 00:22:12,170
- What is it? - Your hands are cold.

249
00:22:12,256 --> 00:22:13,575
l'm sorry.

250
00:22:19,656 --> 00:22:20,805
Breathe deeply.

251
00:22:27,576 --> 00:22:28,975
When was your period?

252
00:22:29,816 --> 00:22:32,569
- Look, is it necessary to..?
- Yes, it is necessary.

253
00:22:33,256 --> 00:22:35,326
All right. Last week.

254
00:22:37,056 --> 00:22:39,889
l'm sure you'd never have
any trouble sleeping.

255
00:22:39,976 --> 00:22:41,329
No, never.

256
00:22:42,336 --> 00:22:43,655
Tell me your secret.

257
00:22:47,816 --> 00:22:50,250
A clear conscience, of course.

258
00:22:51,336 --> 00:22:53,327
That's a neat trick, having
a clear conscience..

259
00:22:53,416 --> 00:22:55,247
..when you work as
a doctor on a ship..

260
00:22:55,336 --> 00:22:58,487
..which has 600 people
living on an open deck.

261
00:22:59,056 --> 00:23:02,173
You know, you just can't take pills
every time you can't sleep..

262
00:23:02,256 --> 00:23:05,726
..or anytime you want to be stimulated
or sedated. lt has its effect.

263
00:23:07,736 --> 00:23:09,249
What are you laughing at?

264
00:23:11,576 --> 00:23:15,967
My house has been burned. They've
taken everything l had.

265
00:23:16,376 --> 00:23:20,972
Now l'm being taken to prison, to
an island l know nothing about.

266
00:23:21,056 --> 00:23:24,332
And you're giving me a
Sunday school sermon.

267
00:23:26,496 --> 00:23:29,772
- You can put your robe
back on now. - Thank you.

268
00:23:33,976 --> 00:23:35,728
You've got a gentle touch.

269
00:23:36,816 --> 00:23:39,649
Maybe you're not as stuffy
as you pretend to be.

270
00:23:40,416 --> 00:23:42,407
No. l hope not.

271
00:23:46,416 --> 00:23:47,644
You gonna help me?

272
00:23:49,816 --> 00:23:51,772
Your doctor may have
helped you too often.

273
00:23:54,656 --> 00:23:57,329
l'm very helpless at this moment.

274
00:23:58,656 --> 00:24:00,726
You can leave me without any help.

275
00:24:01,416 --> 00:24:03,247
That's your prerogative.

276
00:24:15,256 --> 00:24:16,974
This is for tonight only.

277
00:24:20,656 --> 00:24:23,773
- How old are you? - l'm old
enough, as you can see.

278
00:24:23,976 --> 00:24:25,329
Much too old.

279
00:24:26,256 --> 00:24:28,724
- Forty-five? - Not that old.

280
00:24:30,336 --> 00:24:32,804
- How old are you? - Forty-two.

281
00:24:36,176 --> 00:24:38,736
- How old are you? - Forty-one.

282
00:24:39,336 --> 00:24:41,645
- You're joking. - Thank you.

283
00:24:48,656 --> 00:24:49,805
Lie back, please.

284
00:24:54,176 --> 00:24:55,768
You will feel it in a moment.

285
00:24:56,496 --> 00:24:58,168
- Yes. - Talk.

286
00:24:58,896 --> 00:25:02,775
- l beg your pardon? - Talk
until the drug takes effect.

287
00:25:08,056 --> 00:25:10,331
This boat smells of cabbage.

288
00:25:12,336 --> 00:25:16,329
Why does every German
boat smell of cabbage?

289
00:25:16,416 --> 00:25:17,769
Keep talking.

290
00:25:18,816 --> 00:25:20,966
What do you want me to talk about?

291
00:25:21,896 --> 00:25:23,966
Anything you like. Just talk.

292
00:25:28,896 --> 00:25:30,375
What's your name?

293
00:25:30,736 --> 00:25:33,648
- Schumann. - No. Your first name.

294
00:25:35,576 --> 00:25:36,645
Wilhelm.

295
00:25:40,376 --> 00:25:41,650
Wilhelm.

296
00:25:43,976 --> 00:25:45,250
Wilhelm.

297
00:25:47,896 --> 00:25:49,249
lt's perfect.

298
00:25:54,336 --> 00:25:55,564
Perfect.

299
00:26:09,816 --> 00:26:11,249
Stop that now!

300
00:26:14,336 --> 00:26:18,329
- Have you made this trip before?
-Oh l make it at least twice a year.

301
00:26:18,496 --> 00:26:21,568
- Are you in some sort of business?
- l'm in the jewelry business.

302
00:26:21,656 --> 00:26:24,375
A special part. l sell
religious trinkets.

303
00:26:24,456 --> 00:26:27,653
Any religion. You name it, l got it.

304
00:26:27,736 --> 00:26:30,967
l sell neck chains, bracelets,
anklets.

305
00:26:31,056 --> 00:26:32,250
lt sounds like good business.

306
00:26:32,336 --> 00:26:33,815
lt's a very good business.

307
00:26:33,896 --> 00:26:36,649
People feel better when
they wear these things.

308
00:26:36,736 --> 00:26:37,885
l feel good too.

309
00:26:37,976 --> 00:26:41,810
With all this stuff on me, l feel
like an African l met in Paris.

310
00:26:41,896 --> 00:26:46,811
He bought from me a crucifix,
Buddha and mezuzah. All on one chain.

311
00:26:46,896 --> 00:26:48,648
Do you know what he said?

312
00:26:48,976 --> 00:26:52,969
He said, lt may not help,
but it can't hurt.

313
00:26:53,336 --> 00:26:55,645
You seem to get along
very well with people.

314
00:26:55,736 --> 00:26:56,964
Oh l like people.

315
00:26:57,056 --> 00:27:00,332
lf you look for it, you can find
something good in anybody.

316
00:27:00,416 --> 00:27:02,247
lt must be difficult sometimes.

317
00:27:02,336 --> 00:27:06,409
For instance, doesn't it bother you
that you and that little man..

318
00:27:06,496 --> 00:27:09,568
..are the only two Germans who
aren't at the captain's table?

319
00:27:12,896 --> 00:27:17,572
Do you think that bothers me?
Besides, l like that little man.

320
00:27:17,816 --> 00:27:20,410
What kind of a salesman do
you think l would be..

321
00:27:20,496 --> 00:27:22,805
..if l couldn't deal with
a situation like that?

322
00:27:23,896 --> 00:27:25,966
A salesman is supposed
to deal with..

323
00:27:26,056 --> 00:27:28,411
..a difficult situation
and overcome it.

324
00:27:29,496 --> 00:27:31,964
Listen. lt's not a new story.

325
00:27:32,056 --> 00:27:34,889
White men hate black men.
Moslems hate Buddhists.

326
00:27:34,976 --> 00:27:38,332
That's the way it goes. There's
prejudice everywhere.

327
00:27:38,416 --> 00:27:40,327
lt does no good to give it back.

328
00:27:41,256 --> 00:27:43,645
You have got to use your noggin.

329
00:28:02,336 --> 00:28:04,645
There now, you must not mind
not winning against me.

330
00:28:04,736 --> 00:28:07,489
After all, l was Ping-Pong champion
of the Sportsverein in Frankfurt..

331
00:28:07,576 --> 00:28:09,407
..three times over.
- Morning.

332
00:28:09,496 --> 00:28:10,975
- Morning. - Morning.

333
00:28:12,896 --> 00:28:14,807
Herr Freytag picks some
bizarre company.

334
00:28:14,896 --> 00:28:17,171
Ja, l suspect they are
birds of a feather.

335
00:28:17,256 --> 00:28:18,655
Well, shall we play again?

336
00:28:18,736 --> 00:28:20,647
Or perhaps l might suggest
another game.

337
00:28:20,736 --> 00:28:23,569
- What game? - Any game.
One which you might win.

338
00:28:23,656 --> 00:28:25,806
- What game do you mean?
- You have no idea?

339
00:28:25,896 --> 00:28:27,887
l will not let you talk
that way to me.

340
00:28:29,336 --> 00:28:30,974
- l'm sorry. - How dare you!

341
00:28:31,056 --> 00:28:32,375
l could not resist.

342
00:28:32,816 --> 00:28:34,408
l couldn't resist either.

343
00:28:37,816 --> 00:28:39,966
What do your parents feel
about you going to Europe?

344
00:28:40,056 --> 00:28:42,490
My mother's thrilled. lt's
something she's always wanted to do.

345
00:28:42,736 --> 00:28:45,728
l think my father gave me up
for lost a long time ago.

346
00:28:46,496 --> 00:28:49,647
- What do your parents do?
- My father owns a store.

347
00:28:51,496 --> 00:28:53,327
lt's a good store.
A furniture store.

348
00:28:54,176 --> 00:28:56,326
My mother's never been
satisfied with it.

349
00:28:56,816 --> 00:28:59,171
She taught me that a woman had..

350
00:28:59,256 --> 00:29:00,894
..to have something of her very
own outside of her husband..

351
00:29:00,976 --> 00:29:04,252
..otherwise, it was bridge games
and one day a week at the hospital.

352
00:29:05,256 --> 00:29:07,565
What about that young man
you're traveling with?

353
00:29:07,736 --> 00:29:10,967
David. David's an artist.
A wonderful one.

354
00:29:11,816 --> 00:29:14,888
He's a bit caught up with social
consciousness right now..

355
00:29:14,976 --> 00:29:16,329
..but he'll get over that.

356
00:29:16,656 --> 00:29:18,169
ls it serious?

357
00:29:18,896 --> 00:29:22,332
l never felt about anybody
the way l do about David.

358
00:29:23,816 --> 00:29:25,772
l think that David thinks a woman..

359
00:29:25,856 --> 00:29:28,814
..should follow three paces
behind with slippers.

360
00:29:29,896 --> 00:29:31,329
Men usually do.

361
00:29:31,896 --> 00:29:35,252
My husband certainly did. No, thank
you. l have a whiskey sour.

362
00:29:35,416 --> 00:29:38,408
- What did your husband do?
-He was in the diplomatic corps.

363
00:29:38,896 --> 00:29:41,888
Oh.. we put up a wonderful
front in public.

364
00:29:41,976 --> 00:29:44,251
We were everybody's favorite couple.

365
00:29:45,256 --> 00:29:47,724
ln private, it was something
else again.

366
00:29:48,896 --> 00:29:50,329
He was jealous of me.

367
00:29:51,176 --> 00:29:53,485
He was so jealous of
me that he hit me.

368
00:29:54,176 --> 00:29:56,406
He hit me till l bled at the nose.

369
00:29:57,656 --> 00:30:00,250
l was wondering whether
David would beat me.

370
00:30:01,736 --> 00:30:03,328
We quarrel sometimes.

371
00:30:04,256 --> 00:30:05,655
lt seems to come out of nothing..

372
00:30:05,736 --> 00:30:08,569
.. and then it grows into such
ugliness and bitterness.

373
00:30:08,656 --> 00:30:10,248
lt surprises both of us.

374
00:30:12,416 --> 00:30:13,974
l guess a relationship
between a man..

375
00:30:14,056 --> 00:30:16,047
..and a woman is very difficult
these days, isn't it?

376
00:30:17,896 --> 00:30:19,568
Practically impossible.

377
00:30:24,896 --> 00:30:27,171
Put on your beret, Carlos.

378
00:30:34,496 --> 00:30:36,487
Now we can hang in The Prado.

379
00:30:36,656 --> 00:30:40,171
We will hang somewhere, Carlos.
The place is uncertain.

380
00:30:44,056 --> 00:30:47,253
- That's enough for today.
Thank you. - Anytime.

381
00:31:00,576 --> 00:31:02,965
l just can't tell you
how much l admire you.

382
00:31:03,776 --> 00:31:05,175
Why?

383
00:31:05,336 --> 00:31:06,564
You create.

384
00:31:06,816 --> 00:31:08,727
l'm not even sure about that.

385
00:31:08,816 --> 00:31:10,966
l've never been given a
penny for any of this.

386
00:31:11,656 --> 00:31:14,966
Still, l envy you. l envy
you your struggle.

387
00:31:15,256 --> 00:31:18,373
l envy you your doubts
and floundering, even.

388
00:31:18,816 --> 00:31:21,649
And Fraulein Brown.
l envy you that too.

389
00:31:23,256 --> 00:31:25,247
She's an attractive girl, isn't she?

390
00:31:25,496 --> 00:31:27,327
Are you two going to be married?

391
00:31:33,816 --> 00:31:37,252
l am sorry. l don't mean to pry.

392
00:31:37,896 --> 00:31:42,731
You know, the distasteful curiosity
of the non participant.

393
00:31:44,576 --> 00:31:47,488
That's all right. l don't honestly
know whether we'll get married.

394
00:31:47,656 --> 00:31:50,250
l told you how uncertain my life is.

395
00:31:50,416 --> 00:31:52,646
Look l need all the help l can get.

396
00:31:52,776 --> 00:31:56,325
l need someone who can believe in a
man who hasn't proved himself yet.

397
00:31:56,656 --> 00:31:59,329
Someone to be there. Be for me.

398
00:31:59,576 --> 00:32:01,407
Couldn't Fraulein Brown be that?

399
00:32:02,256 --> 00:32:04,326
Fraulein Brown is a modern woman.

400
00:32:04,416 --> 00:32:07,567
Their needs are a lot more
complicated than our mothers' were.

401
00:32:09,896 --> 00:32:12,569
l'm crazy about Jenny. l really am.

402
00:32:12,656 --> 00:32:15,966
l.. l've never felt this way about
anybody, the way l feel about her.

403
00:32:16,816 --> 00:32:19,649
l guess l'm afraid to find out
how apart we really might be.

404
00:32:20,256 --> 00:32:21,575
l see.

405
00:32:23,416 --> 00:32:27,409
l see, l suppose one of the saddest
things in the world must be..

406
00:32:27,896 --> 00:32:31,571
..to see two people who feel
so much for each other..

407
00:32:31,896 --> 00:32:34,774
..and who feel that they
belong together..

408
00:32:34,856 --> 00:32:37,575
..and yet they really don't
belong together at all.

409
00:32:53,576 --> 00:32:54,645
- Hello. - Hello.

410
00:32:54,736 --> 00:32:55,885
What are you doing?

411
00:32:56,976 --> 00:32:58,648
l'm making one of these.

412
00:33:03,816 --> 00:33:06,728
- How many of these
do you have? - Many.

413
00:33:09,896 --> 00:33:11,329
Here is a bull.

414
00:33:12,776 --> 00:33:14,175
A dog.

415
00:33:21,256 --> 00:33:24,726
Do you think anyone in first class
would be interested to buy them?

416
00:33:25,576 --> 00:33:26,770
l would.

417
00:33:43,336 --> 00:33:44,564
Good morning.

418
00:33:45,816 --> 00:33:47,249
Good morning.

419
00:33:48,336 --> 00:33:51,567
- How long have you been here?
- About a half an hour.

420
00:33:52,256 --> 00:33:54,645
No, no, don't get up. Lie back.

421
00:33:55,176 --> 00:33:56,575
Did you put this over me?

422
00:33:56,736 --> 00:33:58,169
Of course.

423
00:33:58,976 --> 00:34:00,728
l'm glad to see you are on deck.

424
00:34:02,776 --> 00:34:05,495
lt was a wonderful drug you
gave me, whatever it was.

425
00:34:06,056 --> 00:34:08,251
What was it, incidentally?

426
00:34:09,896 --> 00:34:11,966
You don't expect me
to tell you, do you?

427
00:34:13,056 --> 00:34:15,331
Oh you can actually laugh.

428
00:34:15,576 --> 00:34:17,328
Did l startle you very much?

429
00:34:18,896 --> 00:34:20,568
lt's good to hear you laugh too.

430
00:34:22,256 --> 00:34:24,816
Did you ever have all
the worst possible..

431
00:34:24,896 --> 00:34:27,330
..things that can happen
to you happen?

432
00:34:28,256 --> 00:34:31,885
Well, it gives you the most
irresponsible feeling.

433
00:34:32,256 --> 00:34:33,814
Nothing more can happen.

434
00:34:40,816 --> 00:34:42,249
Hey!

435
00:34:42,576 --> 00:34:43,770
Are you all right?

436
00:34:46,256 --> 00:34:48,975
lt takes a great deal of courage
to tangle with those two.

437
00:34:50,256 --> 00:34:52,565
l have a certain security with them.

438
00:34:52,896 --> 00:34:55,330
They are the only characters on
the boat smaller than l am.

439
00:34:57,576 --> 00:35:02,650
Such a charming lady makes a
charming morning even more charming.

440
00:35:02,776 --> 00:35:04,255
Thank you.

441
00:35:07,376 --> 00:35:09,253
He's wonderful.

442
00:35:09,416 --> 00:35:10,565
He certainly is.

443
00:35:11,256 --> 00:35:13,406
The one thing about
these children..

444
00:35:13,496 --> 00:35:17,330
..they seem to have a better
time than anyone on the boat.

445
00:35:17,576 --> 00:35:19,567
lf you expect me to speak
a word in defense..

446
00:35:19,656 --> 00:35:21,408
..of those two little monsters,
you're much mistaken.

447
00:35:21,496 --> 00:35:24,806
My prescription for them is to throw
them overboard in a leaky lifeboat.

448
00:35:26,176 --> 00:35:28,326
You didn't have a childhood at all?

449
00:35:28,656 --> 00:35:31,329
Nothing like theirs.
At least, l hope not.

450
00:35:31,416 --> 00:35:37,173
Well.. when l was 4, l persuaded my
little brother to drink lye water.

451
00:35:37,256 --> 00:35:40,168
- Lye water? - Yeah, l
told him it was milk.

452
00:35:40,336 --> 00:35:44,329
So he went to screaming about the
house. His mouth was scrubbed out.

453
00:35:44,416 --> 00:35:47,726
l was beaten black-and-blue.
l meant him no harm.

454
00:35:47,816 --> 00:35:51,331
l was only curious to know
whether it would kill him.

455
00:35:53,176 --> 00:35:54,814
And what about your childhood?

456
00:35:55,496 --> 00:35:58,647
Did nothing gay ever
happen to you at all?

457
00:35:59,256 --> 00:36:00,575
No.

458
00:36:00,656 --> 00:36:02,965
l was the perfect dupe.

459
00:36:03,056 --> 00:36:05,650
l believed anything
anybody ever told me.

460
00:36:05,816 --> 00:36:10,651
l was full of the highest hopes and
the most unbelievable innocence.

461
00:36:11,336 --> 00:36:13,896
However it's true, at the age of 12

462
00:36:13,976 --> 00:36:15,967
..l did have an experience
with the housekeeper..

463
00:36:16,056 --> 00:36:18,251
..that left an indelible
impression on me..

464
00:36:18,336 --> 00:36:21,248
..shocked my mother no end and
cost the poor girl her job.

465
00:36:21,336 --> 00:36:24,885
Well, there is hope
for you after all.

466
00:36:25,816 --> 00:36:29,809
Oh.. the toreros are having
a fiesta tonight.

467
00:36:29,896 --> 00:36:31,568
- l know. - Are you coming?

468
00:36:31,816 --> 00:36:33,374
l wasn't planning to.

469
00:36:33,456 --> 00:36:36,732
l thought we might have
a dance if you did.

470
00:36:37,896 --> 00:36:40,649
Of course, you probably don't dance.

471
00:36:40,816 --> 00:36:44,570
- Exactly how dull do you
think l am? - You are dull.

472
00:36:45,816 --> 00:36:47,249
You're dull..

473
00:36:47,336 --> 00:36:48,564
..stolid..

474
00:36:48,736 --> 00:36:50,249
..unimaginative..

475
00:36:50,656 --> 00:36:51,884
..helpless..

476
00:36:52,176 --> 00:36:53,575
..and charming.

477
00:36:56,056 --> 00:36:57,330
Yes, charming.

478
00:37:01,976 --> 00:37:03,489
Oh you're blushing.

479
00:37:04,336 --> 00:37:07,567
That's the most charming thing l've
ever seen in my whole life.

480
00:37:08,576 --> 00:37:10,567
l've never seen a man blush before.

481
00:37:11,976 --> 00:37:14,729
l'm not blushing. l must
have a temperature.

482
00:37:17,656 --> 00:37:21,569
Well anyway, l'll wear my..
my only dress..

483
00:37:21,976 --> 00:37:26,572
..and l'll give you the choice
of any dance you like.

484
00:37:26,816 --> 00:37:30,729
And l have a feeling it's
gonna be a slow waltz.

485
00:37:30,896 --> 00:37:33,774
l happen to excel in the flamenco.

486
00:37:35,816 --> 00:37:37,727
l was an intellectual.

